ture that's fundamental to computer science. Let's build it from the ground=
 up, just like we're building with LEGOs.</p><p></p><h3>The Big Picture: Wh=
at is a Singly Linked List?</h3><p></p><p>Imagine a treasure hunt. You're g=
iven the first clue. This clue not only tells you something (the "data") bu=
t also points you to where the next clue is hidden. You follow it, find the=
 second clue, which again has some data and points to the third, and so on.=
 The last clue tells you the treasure is here and that there are no more cl=
ues.</p><p>A <b>singly linked list</b> works exactly like this!</p><ul><li>=
<p>Each "clue" is a <b>Node</b>.</p></li><li><p>Each node stores some <b>da=
ta</b> (like an integer, a character, etc.).</p></li><li><p>Each node has a=
 <b>pointer</b> (our "map" to the next clue) that points to the next node i=
n the sequence.</p></li><li><p>The very first node is special; we call it t=
he <b>head</b>. It's our starting point.</p></li><li><p>The very last node'=
s pointer doesn't point to anything. We represent this with <code>NULL</cod=
e>, signifying the end of the list.</p></li></ul><p>This is different from =
an array, where all elements are stored next to each other in a big, contig=
uous block of memory. Linked lists are more flexible because nodes can be s=
cattered all over memory, linked together only by their pointers.</p><hr><p=
