Why This Matters &amp; What's Next?</h3><p></p><p>You've just built one of =
the most essential data structures!</p><p><b>Why it matters:</b></p><ul><li=
><p><b>Dynamic Size</b>: Unlike arrays, you don't need to know the size bef=
orehand. You can add and remove nodes as you please.</p></li><li><p><b>Effi=
cient Insertions/Deletions</b>: Inserting or deleting an element in the mid=
dle of an array is slow because you have to shift all the other elements. W=
ith a linked list, you just have to rewire a couple of pointers!</p></li></=
ul><p>The main drawback is that you can't jump directly to the 50th element=
 like you can with an array (<code>my_array[49]</code>). You have to traver=
se the list from the <code>head</code>.</p><p><b>What's next?</b>
This is just the beginning! This is a <i>singly</i> linked list because it =
only points forward.</p><p>Would you be interested in exploring its cousins=
?</p><ul><li><p><b>Doubly Linked List</b>: Each node has a pointer to the <=
code>next</code> node AND the <code>previous</code> node. This makes moving=
 backward just as easy as moving forward!</p></li><li><p><b>Circular Linked=
 List</b>: The last node, instead of pointing to <code>NULL</code>, points =
back to the <code>head</code>, forming a complete circle!</p></li></ul></di=
